    <weatherForecast/>
    <avalancheActivity>
      <highlights>Slab avalanches are the main danger.</highlights>
      <comment>In particular on steep slopes medium-sized and, in isolated cases, large slab avalanches are possible as a consequence of new snow and strong wind. &lt;br/> The fresh and somewhat older wind slabs can be released by a single winter sport participant in isolated cases on steep shady slopes above approximately 2000 m. This applies in particular at transitions from a shallow to a deep snowpack, when entering gullies and bowls for example. The wind slabs are clearly recognisable to the trained eye. &lt;br/> On slopes small and medium-sized wet avalanches are possible as the day progresses as a consequence of warming during the day.</comment>
    </avalancheActivity>
    <snowpackStructure>
      <comment>10 to 15 cm of snow, and even more in some localities, fell yesterday above approximately 1700 m. &lt;br/> The easterly wind has transported the fresh and old snow. The various wind slabs have bonded with the old snowpack.</comment>
    </snowpackStructure>
